I think that one thing which would help is to give villains goals
which would allow them to win.  One of the big problems with taking
supervillains as credible threats is that they generally have to keep
losing.  If the villains goal is to kill the hero or take over the
world or kill beloved supporting characters in order to get to the
hero then they can't really win.  Okay as Flash #13 showed us the hero
killers can occasionally win but this isn't a paradigm which you can
have repeated very often.  But if you give then goals which they can
accomplish without deranging either the fictional or real world (ie
not killing beloved characters or destroying real world stuff) then
you can have them win.  There's no reason that the criminal can't
occaissionally get away with their schemes.  I remember some interview
with Chris Claremont where he was talking about this in Xmen.  He
talked about how he felt the traditional X villains had lost a lot of
their credibility because they never managed to win.  So he said he
went through a couple of years where the heroes didn't win, at best
they could force a draw but the villains would also win.  I think this
is a case where larger plotlines could come in handy.  Most superhero
books tend to have short story arcs.  The heroes confront some villain
for a couple of issues and then move on to another threat.  If the
plot is longer and the villains plan more labyrinthine then you can
have him accomplish victories, even significant victories, along the
path to his ultimate plan and still have the heroes prevail in the
end.  So Vandal Savage can humiliate the Justice Society and get his
hands on the flux capacitor which he needs to power his doomsday
device but in the climactic battle eight issues down the road the
heroes manage to pull through and barely stop him.  There also might
be an advantage in this regard in team books.  In Flash or Batman we
know that the title character has to pull through but there's more
room for cast changes, deaths, depowerings etc in team books,
especially ones like Runaways which are largely self contained.  This
was one of the things I liked about DnA's version of the Legion.  Not
only were the characters not crossing over to other books often but
the whole book was set in a rarely visited corner of the DCU.  This
let DnA really play with the aftermath of end of the world scenarios
in a way which the regular DCU can't.  Because the DCU and the Marvel
U are supposed to be basically our earth with some additions the
writers can't change it too much.  Hey the Sun Eater almost
extinguishes the sun and freezes the oceans but life goes on.  Hey Lex
Luthor becomes president but there's no real political changes outside
of his rule.  Everything gets reset after the latest apocalypse.
