Too bad Claremont doesn't pay attention to his own ideas.  He's as
guilty as any other writer of writing villains that lose credibility.
Sometimes even when they do win.  (He's also bad for &quot;shock value&quot;
wins that get reversed.  And more often for setting up some amazingly
powerful obstacle, and then having the heroes win by an arbitrary
power-up or new ability, or sheer willpower, or some deus ex machina
revelation.  Which just weakens the whole thing.)
